Resources\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nCourse Catalog\n\n\nCourse Schedule\n\n\nCourse Syllabi\n\n\nCalendar of Events\n\n\n\n\nRequest Information\n\n\nApply Online\n\nGive to CDM\n\n\n\n\n\n\nCDM Home > Student Resources > Forms\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nPage ContentForms LibraryBelow are common forms current students might need over the course of their academic career.\n Actor and Crew Release Form (Non-Student) This form is required for use by students hiring actors or crew members who are not DePaul students when they participate in a DePaul film. The producer and/or director of the film is responsible for obtaining the signed form and retaining it for one year after the completion of the film project.\n Actor Release Form (Non-Student Minor Actor) This form is required for use by students hiring minor actors when they participate in a DePaul film.  The producer and/or director of the film is responsible for obtaining the signed form and retaining it for one year after the completion of the film project.\n\n Actor and Crew Release Form (Student) This form is required for use by all students who are DePaul students when they participate in a DePaul film. The producer and/or director of the film is responsible for obtaining the signed form and retaining it for one year after the completion of the film project.\n Administrative Withdrawal This online form is used by current CDM students to appeal for an exception to the University policy regarding course withdrawal.\n Affidavit of Support This form is used by international students in conjunction with the I-20 application process. \n\n Assistantship Recommendation This form is used ONLY by faculty outside CDM to recommend a current CDM graduate student for a graduate assistantship.\n FERPA Waiver Form, CDM Academic Success Center This form is used by continuing CDM students to grant access to their educational records to a third party.\n FERPA Waiver Form, Office of Graduate Admission This form is used by graduate applicants to CDM to grant access of their educational records to a third party.\n Grade Challenge This form is used by current students to resolve grade disputes.\n Incomplete Request This online form is used by current students to request an incomplete grade.\n Independent Contractor Agreement Anyone working on a DePaul film who is not a DePaul Employee must sign an Independent Contractor Agreement form.\n Independent Study Registration for independent studies are initiated by faculty on the CDM Intranet (under the Faculty tab) once the scope of the course is agreed upon and require final approval from the Associate Dean.\n Internships This online form is used by current students to request an internship for credit.\n Late Enrollment This online form is used by students who experience extreme and extenuating circumstances which prevented them from meeting the university enrollment deadline. The form is to be used by students appealing for late enrollment into CDM courses only.\n Location Use Agreement This form is required for use by a crew member that is filming on a location other than DePaul property.\xa0 The agreement states that their project is covered by DePaul insurance. If the owner is satisfied with this agreement, the student has the owner sign and an approved faculty/staff member signs as a DePaul representative. Copies are made and each of the people signing retains a copy. The producer and/or director of the film is responsible for obtaining the signed form and retaining it for one year after the completion of the film project.\n\n Photo Release Form This form is required when photographing people whose image may be used in internal/external DePaul materials, including social media, advertisements, brochures, magazines, newsletters, and websites.\n Rental Equipment Requests from a Third Party Vendor This form is used when renting equipment from an outside vendor. Only an authorized staff member representing DePaul University may sign equipment rental contracts.\n SAG Student Film Letter of Agreement This form is used to hire an actor who is a member of the Screen Actors Guild (SAG).\n\n SCA Project Information FormThis form and supporting documents must be submitted to the Production Office before equipment or facilities can be reserved for any project outside of a coursework assignment.\n\n SCA Space Reservation FormThis form is used by students to request the use of a CDM-controlled classroom or other facility for auditions, rehearsals, or shoots.\n Transcript Return Request This form is used by international students to request original academic document return. \n\n Transfer Credit Request This form is used by current CDM students to request evaluation and approval of transfer credit. (CDM) at DePaul University invites you to attend our upcoming Graduate Financial Information Session.\n\r\nOur Financial Information Session provides admitted students a comprehensive presentation of the financial aid process, scholarships, and assistantship opportunities, and ways to help finance your advanced degree. There will also be an opportunity after the presentation to speak with a graduate admission officer and financial aid counselor.\n\r\nFor any questions about this event, please call (312) 362-8714.\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\t    12:00 PM to 1:00 PM\r\n\t\t\t    \n\r\n\t\t\t\tOnline\r\n\t\t\t\n\nRegister\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\tMar\r\n\t\t\t\n\r\n\t\t\t\t8\r\n\t\t\t\n\n\n\nCDM Graduate Admission Lunch & Learn: MS Cybersecurity and MS Network Engineering and Security\xa0\n\nEnjoy lunch on us with CDM faculty, current students, and graduate admissions to learn about our MS Cybersecurity and MS Network Engineering and Security programs through conversation in a casual, small setting.\n\r\nAt our Lunch & Learn, you will meet with cybersecurity and network engineering and security faculty members, discuss program interests, learn more about the application process and hear about our students? experiences.\n\r\nLunch and refreshments will be provided. For any questions about this event, please call (312) 362-8714.\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\t    12:30 PM to 1:30 PM\r\n\t\t\t    \n\r\n\t\t\t\tRichard M. and Maggie C. Daley Building - 14 E. Jackson Blvd., Ste. 507\r\n\t\t\t\n\nRegister\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\tMar\r\n\t\t\t\n\r\n\t\t\t\t8\r\n\t\t\t\n\n\n\nCDM Research Colloquium\xa0\n\nFor more information: http://colloquium.cdm.depaul.edu/ \n\n\r\n\t\t\t\t    1:00 PM to 2:00 PM\r\n\t\t\t    \n\r\n\t\t\t\tCDM 708\r\n\t\t\t\n\nNo registration is required for this event.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\tMar\r\n\t\t\t\n\r\n\t\t\t\t8\r\n\t\t\t\n\n\n\nVisiting Artists Series/Department of Mission and Ministry The 39th\xa0\n\nDePaul\'s Visiting Artists Series in partnership with the DePaul\'s Department of Mission and Ministry presents a screening and panel discussion about the feature documentary "The 39th"\nAmidst political scandal and fiscal crisis, 26-year-old activist Will Guzzardi believes that he can mobilize a movement to upend Illinois’ dysfunctional political system. But he chose to run against the daughter of one of the best connected politicians in Chicago — and the establishment is not going to let her go down without a fight. THE 39TH follows Guzzardi as he grows up, from activist to politician, and learns what it really takes for an outsider to win — and govern — within a political machine. TRAILER\xa0https://youtu.be/Ob6e5Cwmatg\nAn on-stage conversation immediately following the film with:\nLaura Fallsgraff\r\nDirector, The 39th\r\nAs Director of Engagement at Chicago production company Kindling Group, Laura Fallsgraff leads strategy and impact for feature films and digital campaigns. After writing for video and digital content for President Obama’s re-election campaign, she joined Kindling Group as a producer and impact producer, working on KG\'s films @home, Radical Grace, and No Small Matter. She premiered her first short documentary, The 39th, in 2017. She loves nothing more than bringing online organizing and compelling storytelling together to inspire change.\nFlonja Hoxha\xa0\r\nPrograms Assistant at Run for Something\r\nFlonja Hoxha is a a third-year studying Political Science at DePaul University. Born and raised in the Chicagoland area Flonja has interned and organized with various local, national, and issue campaigns. Most notably, Biss for Illinois and Hillary for America.\nWill Guzzardi\r\nState Representative, IL 39th District\r\nWill Guzzardi is a state representative from the 39th District, which includes parts of Logan Square, Avondale, Hermosa, Belmont Cragin and Portage Park. He’s been in the legislature since January of 2015. At age 30, he’s one of the youngest members of the Illinois House. Originally from Chapel Hill, North Carolina, Guzzardi attended Brown University, where he graduated with a degree in comparative literature, and has lived in Logan Square ever since. He is passionate about education, and taught after school programs and tutored school children for many years.\nFriday March 8th\r\n5:30pm\nDePaul University\r\nCDM Theatre\r\n247 S. State St. LL105\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\t    5:30 PM to 5:30 PM\r\n\t\t\t    \n\r\n\t\t\t\t247 S. It’s time to set the record straight and credit the pioneering female filmmakers who changed cinema history. Filmmaker and DePaul professor Shayna Connelly invites you to learn about the female filmmakers who pushed the boundaries of cinematic form, starting with filmmakers such as Alice Guy-Blaché, Lois Weber and Germaine Dulac. Celebrate women’s history month with an introduction to the power and influence of these entrepreneurial women.\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\t    7:00 PM to 9:00 PM\r\n\t\t\t    \n\r\n\t\t\t\tChicago Filmmakers 5720 N. 2019\xa0\n\nSCD Symposium 2019\nDePaul University’s College of Computing and Digital Media is proud to announce its 2019 Research Symposium (SCD – Research Symposium).\nThe event will feature student (CDM) at DePaul University invites you to attend our upcoming Graduate Financial Information Session.\n\r\nOur Financial Information Session provides admitted students a comprehensive presentation of the financial aid process, scholarships, and assistantship opportunities, and ways to help finance your advanced degree. But he chose to run against the daughter of one of the best connected politicians in Chicago — and the establishment is not going to let her go down without a fight. THE 39TH follows Guzzardi as he grows up, from activist to politician, and learns what it really takes for an outsider to win — and govern — within a political machine. TRAILER\xa0https://youtu.be/Ob6e5Cwmatg\nAn on-stage conversation immediately following the film with:\nLaura Fallsgraff\r\nDirector, The 39th\r\nAs Director of Engagement at Chicago production company Kindling Group, Laura Fallsgraff leads strategy and impact for feature films and digital campaigns. After writing for video and digital content for President Obama’s re-election campaign, she joined Kindling Group as a producer and impact producer, working on KG\'s films @home, Radical Grace, and No Small Matter. She premiered her first short documentary, The 39th, in 2017. She loves nothing more than bringing online organizing and compelling storytelling together to inspire change.\nFlonja Hoxha\xa0\r\nPrograms Assistant at Run for Something\r\nFlonja Hoxha is a a third-year studying Political Science at DePaul University. Born and raised in the Chicagoland area Flonja has interned and organized with various local, national, and issue campaigns. Most notably, Biss for Illinois and Hillary for America.\nWill Guzzardi\r\nState Representative, IL 39th District\r\nWill Guzzardi is a state representative from the 39th District, which includes parts of Logan Square, Avondale, Hermosa, Belmont Cragin and Portage Park. He’s been in the legislature since January of 2015. At age 30, he’s one of the youngest members of the Illinois House. Originally from Chapel Hill, North Carolina, Guzzardi attended Brown University, where he graduated with a degree in comparative literature, and has lived in Logan Square ever since. He is passionate about education, and taught after school programs and tutored school children for many years.\nFriday March 8th\r\n5:30pm\nDePaul University\r\nCDM Theatre\r\n247 S. State St. LL105\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\t    5:30 PM to 5:30 PM\r\n\t\t\t    \n\r\n\t\t\t\t247 S. It’s time to set the record straight and credit the pioneering female filmmakers who changed cinema history. Filmmaker and DePaul professor Shayna Connelly invites you to learn about the female filmmakers who pushed the boundaries of cinematic form, starting with filmmakers such as Alice Guy-Blaché, Lois Weber and Germaine Dulac. Celebrate women’s history month with an introduction to the power and influence of these entrepreneurial women.\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\t    7:00 PM to 9:00 PM\r\n\t\t\t    \n\r\n\t\t\t\tChicago Filmmakers 5720 N. the financial aid process, scholarships, and assistantship opportunities, and ways to help finance your advanced degree. But he chose to run against the daughter of one of the best connected politicians in Chicago — and the establishment is not going to let her go down without a fight. THE 39TH follows Guzzardi as he grows up, from activist to politician, and learns what it really takes for an outsider to win — and govern — within a political machine. TRAILER\xa0https://youtu.be/Ob6e5Cwmatg\nAn on-stage conversation immediately following the film with:\nLaura Fallsgraff\r\nDirector, The 39th\r\nAs Director of Engagement at Chicago production company Kindling Group, Laura Fallsgraff leads strategy and impact for feature films and digital campaigns. After writing for video and digital content for President Obama’s re-election campaign, she joined Kindling Group as a producer and impact producer, working on KG\'s films @home, Radical Grace, and No Small Matter. She premiered her first short documentary, The 39th, in 2017. She loves nothing more than bringing online organizing and compelling storytelling together to inspire change.\nFlonja Hoxha\xa0\r\nPrograms Assistant at Run for Something\r\nFlonja Hoxha is a a third-year studying Political Science at DePaul University. Born and raised in the Chicagoland area Flonja has interned and organized with various local, national, and issue campaigns. Most notably, Biss for Illinois and Hillary for America.\nWill Guzzardi\r\nState Representative, IL 39th District\r\nWill Guzzardi is a state representative from the 39th District, which includes parts of Logan Square, Avondale, Hermosa, Belmont Cragin and Portage Park. He’s been in the legislature since January of 2015. At age 30, he’s one of the youngest members of the Illinois House. Originally from Chapel Hill, North Carolina, Guzzardi attended Brown University, where he graduated with a degree in comparative literature, and has lived in Logan Square ever since. He is passionate about education, and taught after school programs and tutored school children for many years.\nFriday March 8th\r\n5:30pm\nDePaul University\r\nCDM Theatre\r\n247 S. State St. LL105\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\t    5:30 PM to 5:30 PM\r\n\t\t\t    \n\r\n\t\t\t\t247 S. It’s time to set the record straight and credit the pioneering female filmmakers who changed cinema history. Filmmaker and DePaul professor Shayna Connelly invites you to learn about the female filmmakers who pushed the boundaries of cinematic form, starting with filmmakers such as Alice Guy-Blaché, Lois Weber and Germaine Dulac. Celebrate women’s history month with an introduction to the power and influence of these entrepreneurial women.\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\t    7:00 PM to 9:00 PM\r\n\t\t\t    \n\r\n\t\t\t\tChicago Filmmakers 5720 N. Ridge Ave. 60660 Chicago , IL\r\n\t\t\t\n\nRegister\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\tMar\r\n\t\t\t\n\r\n\t\t\t\t21\r\n\t\t\t\n\n\n\nCDM New Graduate Student Orientation\xa0\n\nJoin your CDM Graduate Admission Officers for our New Graduate Orientation. Meet one-on-one with your admission officer to discuss introductory course waivers, course recommendations and registering.    Check is at 3:45 p.m. and the presentation begins promptly at 4:00 p.m. Light refreshments will be provided. (CDM) at DePaul University invites you to attend our upcoming Graduate Financial Information Session.\n\r\nOur Financial Information Session provides admitted students a comprehensive presentation of the financial aid process, scholarships, and assistantship opportunities, and ways to help finance your advanced degree. But he chose to run against the daughter of one of the best connected politicians in Chicago — and the establishment is not going to let her go down without a fight. THE 39TH follows Guzzardi as he grows up, from activist to politician, and learns what it really takes for an outsider to win — and govern — within a political machine. TRAILER\xa0https://youtu.be/Ob6e5Cwmatg\nAn on-stage conversation immediately following the film with:\nLaura Fallsgraff\r\nDirector, The 39th\r\nAs Director of Engagement at Chicago production company Kindling Group, Laura Fallsgraff leads strategy and impact for feature films and digital campaigns. After writing for video and digital content for President Obama’s re-election campaign, she joined Kindling Group as a producer and impact producer, working on KG\'s films @home, Radical Grace, and No Small Matter. She premiered her first short documentary, The 39th, in 2017. She loves nothing more than bringing online organizing and compelling storytelling together to inspire change.\nFlonja Hoxha\xa0\r\nPrograms Assistant at Run for Something\r\nFlonja Hoxha is a a third-year studying Political Science at DePaul University. Born and raised in the Chicagoland area Flonja has interned and organized with various local, national, and issue campaigns. Most notably, Biss for Illinois and Hillary for America.\nWill Guzzardi\r\nState Representative, IL 39th District\r\nWill Guzzardi is a state representative from the 39th District, which includes parts of Logan Square, Avondale, Hermosa, Belmont Cragin and Portage Park. He’s been in the legislature since January of 2015. At age 30, he’s one of the youngest members of the Illinois House. Originally from Chapel Hill, North Carolina, Guzzardi attended Brown University, where he graduated with a degree in comparative literature, and has lived in Logan Square ever since. He is passionate about education, and taught after school programs and tutored school children for many years.\nFriday March 8th\r\n5:30pm\nDePaul University\r\nCDM Theatre\r\n247 S. State St. LL105\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\t    5:30 PM to 5:30 PM\r\n\t\t\t    \n\r\n\t\t\t\t247 S. LL107\r\n\t\t\t\n\nRegister\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\tMar\r\n\t\t\t\n\r\n\t\t\t\t15\r\n\t\t\t\n\n\n\nCDM Research Colloquium \xa0\n\n\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\t    1:00 PM to 2:00 PM\r\n\t\t\t    \n\r\n\t\t\t\tCDM 708\r\n\t\t\t\n\ncolloquium.cdm.depaul.edu \n\n\n\n\n\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\tMar\r\n\t\t\t\n\r\n\t\t\t\t15\r\n\t\t\t\n\n\n\nPhD 101\xa0\n\nLearn more about getting a PhD and pursuing research opportunities at CDM.\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\t    3:00 PM to 5:00 PM\r\n\t\t\t    \n\r\n\t\t\t\tCDM 708\r\n\t\t\t\n\nNo registration is required for this event.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\tMar\r\n\t\t\t\n\r\n\t\t\t\t16\r\n\t\t\t\n\n\n\nLecture- An Alternative History of Cinema: Female Pioneers\xa0\n\nLecture presented by Shayna Connelly\nWomen have played an integral role in cinema from the beginning, but their achievements have not always been recognized. It’s time to set the record straight and credit the pioneering female filmmakers who changed cinema history. Filmmaker and DePaul professor Shayna Connelly invites you to learn about the female filmmakers who pushed the boundaries of cinematic form, starting with filmmakers such as Alice Guy-Blaché, Lois Weber and Germaine Dulac. Celebrate women’s history month with an introduction to the power and influence of these entrepreneurial women.\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\t    7:00 PM to 9:00 PM\r\n\t\t\t    \n\r\n\t\t\t\tChicago Filmmakers 5720 N. Ridge Ave. 60660 Chicago , IL\r\n\t\t\t\n\nRegister\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\tMar\r\n\t\t\t\n\r\n\t\t\t\t21\r\n\t\t\t\n\n\n\nCDM New Graduate Student Orientation\xa0\n\nJoin your CDM Graduate Admission Officers for our New Graduate Orientation. Newly admitted students will learn how to register for classes, navigating Campus Connect, and useful tips for program management.    Meet one-on-one with your admission officer to discuss introductory course waivers, course recommendations and registering.    Check is at 3:45 p.m. and the presentation begins promptly at 4:00 p.m. Light refreshments will be provided. But he chose to run against the daughter of one of the best connected politicians in Chicago — and the establishment is not going to let her go down without a fight. THE 39TH follows Guzzardi as he grows up, from activist to politician, and learns what it really takes for an outsider to win — and govern — within a political machine. TRAILER\xa0https://youtu.be/Ob6e5Cwmatg\nAn on-stage conversation immediately following the film with:\nLaura Fallsgraff\r\nDirector, The 39th\r\nAs Director of Engagement at Chicago production company Kindling Group, Laura Fallsgraff leads strategy and impact for feature films and digital campaigns. After writing for video and digital content for President Obama’s re-election campaign, she joined Kindling Group as a producer and impact producer, working on KG\'s films @home, Radical Grace, and No Small Matter. She premiered her first short documentary, The 39th, in 2017. She loves nothing more than bringing online organizing and compelling storytelling together to inspire change.\nFlonja Hoxha\xa0\r\nPrograms Assistant at Run for Something\r\nFlonja Hoxha is a a third-year studying Political Science at DePaul University. Born and raised in the Chicagoland area Flonja has interned and organized with various local, national, and issue campaigns. Most notably, Biss for Illinois and Hillary for America.\nWill Guzzardi\r\nState Representative, IL 39th District\r\nWill Guzzardi is a state representative from the 39th District, which includes parts of Logan Square, Avondale, Hermosa, Belmont Cragin and Portage Park. He’s been in the legislature since January of 2015. At age 30, he’s one of the youngest members of the Illinois House. Originally from Chapel Hill, North Carolina, Guzzardi attended Brown University, where he graduated with a degree in comparative literature, and has lived in Logan Square ever since. He is passionate about education, and taught after school programs and tutored school children for many years.\nFriday March 8th\r\n5:30pm\nDePaul University\r\nCDM Theatre\r\n247 S. It’s time to set the record straight and credit the pioneering female filmmakers who changed cinema history. Filmmaker and DePaul professor Shayna Connelly invites you to learn about the female filmmakers who pushed the boundaries of cinematic form, starting with filmmakers such as Alice Guy-Blaché, Lois Weber and Germaine Dulac. Celebrate women’s history month with an introduction to the power and influence of these entrepreneurial women.\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\t    7:00 PM to 9:00 PM\r\n\t\t\t    \n\r\n\t\t\t\tChicago Filmmakers 5720 N. (CDM) at DePaul University invites you to attend our upcoming Graduate Financial Information Session.\n\r\nOur Financial Information Session provides admitted students a comprehensive presentation of the financial aid process, scholarships, and assistantship opportunities, and ways to help finance your advanced degree. There will also be an opportunity after the presentation to speak with a graduate admission officer and financial aid counselor.\n\r\nFor any questions about this event, please call (312) 362-8714.\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\t    12:00 PM to 1:00 PM\r\n\t\t\t    \n\r\n\t\t\t\tOnline\r\n\t\t\t\n\nRegister\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\tMar\r\n\t\t\t\n\r\n\t\t\t\t8\r\n\t\t\t\n\n\n\nCDM Graduate Admission Lunch & Learn: MS Cybersecurity and MS Network Engineering and Security\xa0\n\nEnjoy lunch on us with CDM faculty, current students, and graduate admissions to learn about our MS Cybersecurity and MS Network Engineering and Security programs through conversation in a casual, small setting.\n\r\nAt our Lunch & Learn, you will meet with cybersecurity and network engineering and security faculty members, discuss program interests, learn more about the application process and hear about our students? experiences.\n\r\nLunch and refreshments will be provided. For any questions about this event, please call (312) 362-8714.\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\t    12:30 PM to 1:30 PM\r\n\t\t\t    \n\r\n\t\t\t\tRichard M. and Maggie C. Daley Building - 14 E. Jackson Blvd., Ste. 507\r\n\t\t\t\n\nRegister\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\tMar\r\n\t\t\t\n\r\n\t\t\t\t8\r\n\t\t\t\n\n\n\nCDM Research Colloquium\xa0\n\nFor more information: http://colloquium.cdm.depaul.edu/ \n\n\r\n\t\t\t\t    1:00 PM to 2:00 PM\r\n\t\t\t    \n\r\n\t\t\t\tCDM 708\r\n\t\t\t\n\nNo registration is required for this event.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\tMar\r\n\t\t\t\n\r\n\t\t\t\t8\r\n\t\t\t\n\n\n\nVisiting Artists Series/Department of Mission and Ministry The 39th\xa0\n\nDePaul\'s Visiting Artists Series in partnership with the DePaul\'s Department of Mission and Ministry presents a screening and panel discussion about the feature documentary "The 39th"\nAmidst political scandal and fiscal crisis, 26-year-old activist Will Guzzardi believes that he can mobilize a movement to upend Illinois’ dysfunctional political system. But he chose to run against the daughter of one of the best connected politicians in Chicago — and the establishment is not going to let her go down without a fight. THE 39TH follows Guzzardi as he grows up, from activist to politician, and learns what it really takes for an outsider to win — and govern — within a political machine. TRAILER\xa0https://youtu.be/Ob6e5Cwmatg\nAn on-stage conversation immediately following the film with:\nLaura Fallsgraff\r\nDirector, The 39th\r\nAs Director of Engagement at Chicago production company Kindling Group, Laura Fallsgraff leads strategy and impact for feature films and digital campaigns. After writing for video and digital content for President Obama’s re-election campaign, she joined Kindling Group as a producer and impact producer, working on KG\'s films @home, Radical Grace, and No Small Matter. She premiered her first short documentary, The 39th, in 2017. She loves nothing more than bringing online organizing and compelling storytelling together to inspire change.\nFlonja Hoxha\xa0\r\nPrograms Assistant at Run for Something\r\nFlonja Hoxha is a a third-year studying Political Science at DePaul University. Born and raised in the Chicagoland area Flonja has interned and organized with various local, national, and issue campaigns. Most notably, Biss for Illinois and Hillary for America.\nWill Guzzardi\r\nState Representative, IL 39th District\r\nWill Guzzardi is a state representative from the 39th District, which includes parts of Logan Square, Avondale, Hermosa, Belmont Cragin and Portage Park. He’s been in the legislature since January of 2015. At age 30, he’s one of the youngest members of the Illinois House. Originally from Chapel Hill, North Carolina, Guzzardi attended Brown University, where he graduated with a degree in comparative literature, and has lived in Logan Square ever since. He is passionate about education, and taught after school programs and tutored school children for many years.\nFriday March 8th\r\n5:30pm\nDePaul University\r\nCDM Theatre\r\n247 S. State St. LL105\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\t    5:30 PM to 5:30 PM\r\n\t\t\t    \n\r\n\t\t\t\t247 S. It’s time to set the record straight and credit the pioneering female filmmakers who changed cinema history. Filmmaker and DePaul professor Shayna Connelly invites you to learn about the female filmmakers who pushed the boundaries of cinematic form, starting with filmmakers such as Alice Guy-Blaché, Lois Weber and Germaine Dulac. Celebrate women’s history month with an introduction to the power and influence of these entrepreneurial women.\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\t    7:00 PM to 9:00 PM\r\n\t\t\t    \n\r\n\t\t\t\tChicago Filmmakers 5720 N. Ridge Ave. 60660 Chicago , IL\r\n\t\t\t\n\nRegister\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\tMar\r\n\t\t\t\n\r\n\t\t\t\t21\r\n\t\t\t\n\n\n\nCDM New Graduate Student Orientation\xa0\n\nJoin your CDM Graduate Admission Officers for our New Graduate Orientation. Meet one-on-one with your admission officer to discuss introductory course waivers, course recommendations and registering.    Check is at 3:45 p.m. and the presentation begins promptly at 4:00 p.m. Light refreshments will be provided.    This event is intended for newly admitted graduate students enrolling in the Spring Quarter 2019. 2019\xa0\n\nSCD Symposium 2019\nDePaul University’s College of Computing and Digital Media is proud to announce its 2019 Research Symposium (SCD – Research Symposium).\nThe event will feature student presentations and posters\xa0take place on:\nFriday May 31st, 2019\r\nCollege of Computing and Digital Media, room 924\r\n243 S Wabash Ave\r\nChicago, IL 60604\nThe event is a fantastic\xa0opportunity for students at all levels to present research or attend to engage with the research community at DePaul.\nThis year’s event is being sponsored by the Dean’s Office of the College of Computing and Digital Media (CDM) and organized by the PhD Student Council (PSC@CDM).\nSubmissions and requirements are clarified in the\xa0Call for Papers\xa0tab on the website.\nPlease RSVP if you plan to (CDM) at DePaul University invites you to attend our upcoming Graduate Financial Information Session.\n\r\nOur Financial Information Session provides admitted students a comprehensive presentation of the financial aid process, scholarships, and assistantship opportunities, and ways to help finance your advanced degree. There will also be an opportunity after the presentation to speak with a graduate admission officer and financial aid counselor.\n\r\nFor any questions about this event, please call (312) 362-8714.\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\t    12:00 PM to 1:00 PM\r\n\t\t\t    \n\r\n\t\t\t\tOnline\r\n\t\t\t\n\nRegister\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\tMar\r\n\t\t\t\n\r\n\t\t\t\t8\r\n\t\t\t\n\n\n\nCDM Graduate Admission Lunch & Learn: MS Cybersecurity and MS Network Engineering and Security\xa0\n\nEnjoy lunch on us with CDM faculty, current students, and graduate admissions to learn about our MS Cybersecurity and MS Network Engineering and Security programs through conversation in a casual, small setting.\n\r\nAt our Lunch & Learn, you will meet with cybersecurity and network engineering and security faculty members, discuss program interests, learn more about the application process and hear about our students? experiences.\n\r\nLunch and refreshments will be provided. For any questions about this event, please call (312) 362-8714.\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\t    12:30 PM to 1:30 PM\r\n\t\t\t    \n\r\n\t\t\t\tRichard M. and Maggie C. Daley Building - 14 E. Jackson Blvd., Ste. 507\r\n\t\t\t\n\nRegister\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\tMar\r\n\t\t\t\n\r\n\t\t\t\t8\r\n\t\t\t\n\n\n\nCDM Research Colloquium\xa0\n\nFor more information: http://colloquium.cdm.depaul.edu/ \n\n\r\n\t\t\t\t    1:00 PM to 2:00 PM\r\n\t\t\t    \n\r\n\t\t\t\tCDM 708\r\n\t\t\t\n\nNo registration is required for this event.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\tMar\r\n\t\t\t\n\r\n\t\t\t\t8\r\n\t\t\t\n\n\n\nVisiting Artists Series/Department of Mission and Ministry The 39th\xa0\n\nDePaul\'s Visiting Artists Series in partnership with the DePaul\'s Department of Mission and Ministry presents a screening and panel discussion about the feature documentary "The 39th"\nAmidst political scandal and fiscal crisis, 26-year-old activist Will Guzzardi believes that he can mobilize a movement to upend Illinois’ dysfunctional political system. But he chose to run against the daughter of one of the best connected politicians in Chicago — and the establishment is not going to let her go down without a fight. THE 39TH follows Guzzardi as he grows up, from activist to politician, and learns what it really takes for an outsider to win — and govern — within a political machine. TRAILER\xa0https://youtu.be/Ob6e5Cwmatg\nAn on-stage conversation immediately following the film with:\nLaura Fallsgraff\r\nDirector, The 39th\r\nAs Director of Engagement at Chicago production company Kindling Group, Laura Fallsgraff leads strategy and impact for feature films and digital campaigns. After writing for video and digital content for President Obama’s re-election campaign, she joined Kindling Group as a producer and impact producer, working on KG\'s films @home, Radical Grace, and No Small Matter. She premiered her first short documentary, The 39th, in 2017. She loves nothing more than bringing online organizing and compelling storytelling together to inspire change.\nFlonja Hoxha\xa0\r\nPrograms Assistant at Run for Something\r\nFlonja Hoxha is a a third-year studying Political Science at DePaul University. Born and raised in the Chicagoland area Flonja has interned and organized with various local, national, and issue campaigns. Most notably, Biss for Illinois and Hillary for America.\nWill Guzzardi\r\nState Representative, IL 39th District\r\nWill Guzzardi is a state representative from the 39th District, which includes parts of Logan Square, Avondale, Hermosa, Belmont Cragin and Portage Park. He’s been in the legislature since January of 2015. At age 30, he’s one of the youngest members of the Illinois House. Originally from Chapel Hill, North Carolina, Guzzardi attended Brown University, where he graduated with a degree in comparative literature, and has lived in Logan Square ever since. He is passionate about education, and taught after school programs and tutored school children for many years.\nFriday March 8th\r\n5:30pm\nDePaul University\r\nCDM Theatre\r\n247 S. State St. LL105\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\t    5:30 PM to 5:30 PM\r\n\t\t\t    \n\r\n\t\t\t\t247 S. It’s time to set the record straight and credit the pioneering female filmmakers who changed cinema history. Filmmaker and DePaul professor Shayna Connelly invites you to learn about the female filmmakers who pushed the boundaries of cinematic form, starting with filmmakers such as Alice Guy-Blaché, Lois Weber and Germaine Dulac. Celebrate women’s history month with an introduction to the power and influence of these entrepreneurial women.\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\t    7:00 PM to 9:00 PM\r\n\t\t\t    \n\r\n\t\t\t\tChicago Filmmakers 5720 N. 2019\xa0\n\nSCD Symposium 2019\nDePaul University’s College of Computing and Digital Media is proud to announce its 2019 Research Symposium (SCD – Research Symposium).\nThe event will feature student         if ($(this).nextAll(\'.st-content\').css(\'display\') == \'none\') {\r\n                $(this).children(\'span\').addClass(\'st-open\');\r\n            }\r\n            else {\r\n (CDM) at DePaul University invites you to attend our upcoming Graduate Financial Information Session.\n\r\nOur Financial Information Session provides admitted students a comprehensive presentation of the financial aid process, scholarships, and assistantship opportunities, and ways to help finance your advanced degree. There will also be an opportunity after the presentation to speak with a graduate admission officer and financial aid counselor.\n\r\nFor any questions about this event, please call (312) 362-8714.\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\t    12:00 PM to 1:00 PM\r\n\t\t\t    \n\r\n\t\t\t\tOnline\r\n\t\t\t\n\nRegister\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\tMar\r\n\t\t\t\n\r\n\t\t\t\t8\r\n\t\t\t\n\n\n\nCDM Graduate Admission Lunch & Learn: MS Cybersecurity and MS Network Engineering and Security\xa0\n\nEnjoy lunch on us with CDM faculty, current students, and graduate admissions to learn about our MS Cybersecurity and MS Network Engineering and Security programs through conversation in a casual, small setting.\n\r\nAt our Lunch & Learn, you will meet with cybersecurity and network engineering and security faculty members, discuss program interests, learn more about the application process and hear about our students? experiences.\n\r\nLunch and refreshments will be provided. For any questions about this event, please call (312) 362-8714.\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\t    12:30 PM to 1:30 PM\r\n\t\t\t    \n\r\n\t\t\t\tRichard M. and Maggie C. Daley Building - 14 E. Jackson Blvd., Ste. 507\r\n\t\t\t\n\nRegister\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\tMar\r\n\t\t\t\n\r\n\t\t\t\t8\r\n\t\t\t\n\n\n\nCDM Research Colloquium\xa0\n\nFor more information: http://colloquium.cdm.depaul.edu/ \n\n\r\n\t\t\t\t    1:00 PM to 2:00 PM\r\n\t\t\t    \n\r\n\t\t\t\tCDM 708\r\n\t\t\t\n\nNo registration is required for this event.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\tMar\r\n\t\t\t\n\r\n\t\t\t\t8\r\n\t\t\t\n\n\n\nVisiting Artists Series/Department of Mission and Ministry The 39th\xa0\n\nDePaul\'s Visiting Artists Series in partnership with the DePaul\'s Department of Mission and Ministry presents a screening and panel discussion about the feature documentary "The 39th"\nAmidst political scandal and fiscal crisis, 26-year-old activist Will Guzzardi believes that he can mobilize a movement to upend Illinois’ dysfunctional political system. But he chose to run against the daughter of one of the best connected politicians in Chicago — and the establishment is not going to let her go down without a fight. THE 39TH follows Guzzardi as he grows up, from activist to politician, and learns what it really takes for an outsider to win — and govern — within a political machine. TRAILER\xa0https://youtu.be/Ob6e5Cwmatg\nAn on-stage conversation immediately following the film with:\nLaura Fallsgraff\r\nDirector, The 39th\r\nAs Director of Engagement at Chicago production company Kindling Group, Laura Fallsgraff leads strategy and impact for feature films and digital campaigns. After writing for video and digital content for President Obama’s re-election campaign, she joined Kindling Group as a producer and impact producer, working on KG\'s films @home, Radical Grace, and No Small Matter. She premiered her first short documentary, The 39th, in 2017. She loves nothing more than bringing online organizing and compelling storytelling together to inspire change.\nFlonja Hoxha\xa0\r\nPrograms Assistant at Run for Something\r\nFlonja Hoxha is a a third-year studying Political Science at DePaul University. Born and raised in the Chicagoland area Flonja has interned and organized with various local, national, and issue campaigns. Most notably, Biss for Illinois and Hillary for America.\nWill Guzzardi\r\nState Representative, IL 39th District\r\nWill Guzzardi is a state representative from the 39th District, which includes parts of Logan Square, Avondale, Hermosa, Belmont Cragin and Portage Park. He’s been in the legislature since January of 2015. At age 30, he’s one of the youngest members of the Illinois House. Originally from Chapel Hill, North Carolina, Guzzardi attended Brown University, where he graduated with a degree in comparative literature, and has lived in Logan Square ever since. He is passionate about education, and taught after school programs and tutored school children for many years.\nFriday March 8th\r\n5:30pm\nDePaul University\r\nCDM Theatre\r\n247 S. State St. LL105\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\t    5:30 PM to 5:30 PM\r\n\t\t\t    \n\r\n\t\t\t\t247 S. It’s time to set the record straight and credit the pioneering female filmmakers who changed cinema history. Filmmaker and DePaul professor Shayna Connelly invites you to learn about the female filmmakers who pushed the boundaries of cinematic form, starting with filmmakers such as Alice Guy-Blaché, Lois Weber and Germaine Dulac. Celebrate women’s history month with an introduction to the power and influence of these entrepreneurial women.\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\t    7:00 PM to 9:00 PM\r\n\t\t\t    \n\r\n\t\t\t\tChicago Filmmakers 5720 N. (CDM) at DePaul University invites you to attend our upcoming Graduate Financial Information Session.\n\r\nOur Financial Information Session provides admitted students a comprehensive presentation of the financial aid process, scholarships, and assistantship opportunities, and ways to help finance your advanced degree. There will also be an opportunity after the presentation to speak with a graduate admission officer and financial aid counselor.\n\r\nFor any questions about this event, please call (312) 362-8714.\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\t    12:00 PM to 1:00 PM\r\n\t\t\t    \n\r\n\t\t\t\tOnline\r\n\t\t\t\n\nRegister\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\tMar\r\n\t\t\t\n\r\n\t\t\t\t8\r\n\t\t\t\n\n\n\nCDM Graduate Admission Lunch & Learn: MS Cybersecurity and MS Network Engineering and Security\xa0\n\nEnjoy lunch on us with CDM faculty, current students, and graduate admissions to learn about our MS Cybersecurity and MS Network Engineering and Security programs through conversation in a casual, small setting.\n\r\nAt our Lunch & Learn, you will meet with cybersecurity and network engineering and security faculty members, discuss program interests, learn more about the application process and hear about our students? experiences.\n\r\nLunch and refreshments will be provided. For any questions about this event, please call (312) 362-8714.\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\t    12:30 PM to 1:30 PM\r\n\t\t\t    \n\r\n\t\t\t\tRichard M. and Maggie C. Daley Building - 14 E. Jackson Blvd., Ste. 507\r\n\t\t\t\n\nRegister\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\tMar\r\n\t\t\t\n\r\n\t\t\t\t8\r\n\t\t\t\n\n\n\nCDM Research Colloquium\xa0\n\nFor more information: http://colloquium.cdm.depaul.edu/ \n\n\r\n\t\t\t\t    1:00 PM to 2:00 PM\r\n\t\t\t    \n\r\n\t\t\t\tCDM 708\r\n\t\t\t\n\nNo registration is required for this event.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\tMar\r\n\t\t\t\n\r\n\t\t\t\t8\r\n\t\t\t\n\n\n\nVisiting Artists Series/Department of Mission and Ministry The 39th\xa0\n\nDePaul\'s Visiting Artists Series in partnership with the DePaul\'s Department of Mission and Ministry presents a screening and panel discussion about the feature documentary "The 39th"\nAmidst political scandal and fiscal crisis, 26-year-old activist Will Guzzardi believes that he can mobilize a movement to upend Illinois’ dysfunctional political system. But he chose to run against the daughter of one of the best connected politicians in Chicago — and the establishment is not going to let her go down without a fight. THE 39TH follows Guzzardi as he grows up, from activist to politician, and learns what it really takes for an outsider to win — and govern — within a political machine. TRAILER\xa0https://youtu.be/Ob6e5Cwmatg\nAn on-stage conversation immediately following the film with:\nLaura Fallsgraff\r\nDirector, The 39th\r\nAs Director of Engagement at Chicago production company Kindling Group, Laura Fallsgraff leads strategy and impact for feature films and digital campaigns. After writing for video and digital content for President Obama’s re-election campaign, she joined Kindling Group as a producer and impact producer, working on KG\'s films @home, Radical Grace, and No Small Matter. She premiered her first short documentary, The 39th, in 2017. She loves nothing more than bringing online organizing and compelling storytelling together to inspire change.\nFlonja Hoxha\xa0\r\nPrograms Assistant at Run for Something\r\nFlonja Hoxha is a a third-year studying Political Science at DePaul University. Born and raised in the Chicagoland area Flonja has interned and organized with various local, national, and issue campaigns. Most notably, Biss for Illinois and Hillary for America.\nWill Guzzardi\r\nState Representative, IL 39th District\r\nWill Guzzardi is a state representative from the 39th District, which includes parts of Logan Square, Avondale, Hermosa, Belmont Cragin and Portage Park. He’s been in the legislature since January of 2015. At age 30, he’s one of the youngest members of the Illinois House. Originally from Chapel Hill, North Carolina, Guzzardi attended Brown University, where he graduated with a degree in comparative literature, and has lived in Logan Square ever since. He is passionate about education, and taught after school programs and tutored school children for many years.\nFriday March 8th\r\n5:30pm\nDePaul University\r\nCDM Theatre\r\n247 S. State St. LL105\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\t    5:30 PM to 5:30 PM\r\n\t\t\t    \n\r\n\t\t\t\t247 S. It’s time to set the record straight and credit the pioneering female filmmakers who changed cinema history. Filmmaker and DePaul professor Shayna Connelly invites you to learn about the female filmmakers who pushed the boundaries of cinematic form, starting with filmmakers such as Alice Guy-Blaché, Lois Weber and Germaine Dulac. Celebrate women’s history month with an introduction to the power and influence of these entrepreneurial women.\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\t    7:00 PM to 9:00 PM\r\n\t\t\t    \n\r\n\t\t\t\tChicago Filmmakers 5720 N. (CDM) at DePaul University invites you to attend our upcoming Graduate Financial Information Session.\n\r\nOur Financial Information Session provides admitted students a comprehensive presentation of the financial aid process, scholarships, and assistantship opportunities, and ways to help finance your advanced degree. There will also be an opportunity after the presentation to speak with a graduate admission officer and financial aid counselor.\n\r\nFor any questions about this event, please call (312) 362-8714.\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\t    12:00 PM to 1:00 PM\r\n\t\t\t    \n\r\n\t\t\t\tOnline\r\n\t\t\t\n\nRegister\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\tMar\r\n\t\t\t\n\r\n\t\t\t\t8\r\n\t\t\t\n\n\n\nCDM Graduate Admission Lunch & Learn: MS Cybersecurity and MS Network Engineering and Security\xa0\n\nEnjoy lunch on us with CDM faculty, current students, and graduate admissions to learn about our MS Cybersecurity and MS Network Engineering and Security programs through conversation in a casual, small setting.\n\r\nAt our Lunch & Learn, you will meet with cybersecurity and network engineering and security faculty members, discuss program interests, learn more about the application process and hear about our students? experiences.\n\r\nLunch and refreshments will be provided. Jackson Blvd., Ste. 507\r\n\t\t\t\n\nRegister\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\tMar\r\n\t\t\t\n\r\n\t\t\t\t8\r\n\t\t\t\n\n\n\nCDM Research Colloquium\xa0\n\nFor more information: http://colloquium.cdm.depaul.edu/ \n\n\r\n\t\t\t\t    1:00 PM to 2:00 PM\r\n\t\t\t    \n\r\n\t\t\t\tCDM 708\r\n\t\t\t\n\nNo registration is required for this event.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\tMar\r\n\t\t\t\n\r\n\t\t\t\t8\r\n\t\t\t\n\n\n\nVisiting Artists Series/Department of Mission and Ministry The 39th\xa0\n\nDePaul\'s Visiting Artists Series in partnership with the DePaul\'s Department of Mission and Ministry presents a screening and panel discussion about the feature documentary "The 39th"\nAmidst political scandal and fiscal crisis, 26-year-old activist Will Guzzardi believes that he can mobilize a movement to upend Illinois’ dysfunctional political system. But he chose to run against the daughter of one of the best connected politicians in Chicago — and the establishment is not going to let her go down without a fight. THE 39TH follows Guzzardi as he grows up, from activist to politician, and learns what it really takes for an outsider to win — and govern — within a political machine. TRAILER\xa0https://youtu.be/Ob6e5Cwmatg\nAn on-stage conversation immediately following the film with:\nLaura Fallsgraff\r\nDirector, The 39th\r\nAs Director of Engagement at Chicago production company Kindling Group, Laura Fallsgraff leads strategy and impact for feature films and digital campaigns. After writing for video and digital content for President Obama’s re-election campaign, she joined Kindling Group as a producer and impact producer, working on KG\'s films @home, Radical Grace, and No Small Matter. She premiered her first short documentary, The 39th, in 2017. She loves nothing more than bringing online organizing and compelling storytelling together to inspire change.\nFlonja Hoxha\xa0\r\nPrograms Assistant at Run for Something\r\nFlonja Hoxha is a a third-year studying Political Science at DePaul University. Born and raised in the Chicagoland area Flonja has interned and organized with various local, national, and issue campaigns. Most notably, Biss for Illinois and Hillary for America.\nWill Guzzardi\r\nState Representative, IL 39th District\r\nWill Guzzardi is a state representative from the 39th District, which includes parts of Logan Square, Avondale, Hermosa, Belmont Cragin and Portage Park. He’s been in the legislature since January of 2015. At age 30, he’s one of the youngest members of the Illinois House. Originally from Chapel Hill, North Carolina, Guzzardi attended Brown University, where he graduated with a degree in comparative literature, and has lived in Logan Square ever since. He is passionate about education, and taught after school programs and tutored school children for many years.\nFriday March 8th\r\n5:30pm\nDePaul University\r\nCDM Theatre\r\n247 S. It’s time to set the record straight and credit the pioneering female filmmakers who changed cinema history. Filmmaker and DePaul professor Shayna Connelly invites you to learn about the female filmmakers who pushed the boundaries of cinematic form, starting with filmmakers such as Alice Guy-Blaché, Lois Weber and Germaine Dulac. Celebrate women’s history month with an introduction to the power and influence of these entrepreneurial women.\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\t    7:00 PM to 9:00 PM\r\n\t\t\t    \n\r\n\t\t\t\tChicago Filmmakers 5720 N. But he chose to run against the daughter of one of the best connected politicians in Chicago — and the establishment is not going to let her go down without a fight. THE 39TH follows Guzzardi as he grows up, from activist to politician, and learns what it really takes for an outsider to win — and govern — within a political machine. TRAILER\xa0https://youtu.be/Ob6e5Cwmatg\nAn on-stage conversation immediately following the film with:\nLaura Fallsgraff\r\nDirector, The 39th\r\nAs Director of Engagement at Chicago production company Kindling Group, Laura Fallsgraff leads strategy and impact for feature films and digital campaigns. After writing for video and digital content for President Obama’s re-election campaign, she joined Kindling Group as a producer and impact producer, working on KG\'s films @home, Radical Grace, and No Small Matter. She premiered her first short documentary, The 39th, in 2017. She loves nothing more than bringing online organizing and compelling storytelling together to inspire change.\nFlonja Hoxha\xa0\r\nPrograms Assistant at Run for Something\r\nFlonja Hoxha is a a third-year studying Political Science at DePaul University. Born and raised in the Chicagoland area Flonja has interned and organized with various local, national, and issue campaigns. Most notably, Biss for Illinois and Hillary for America.\nWill Guzzardi\r\nState Representative, IL 39th District\r\nWill Guzzardi is a state representative from the 39th District, which includes parts of Logan Square, Avondale, Hermosa, Belmont Cragin and Portage Park. He’s been in the legislature since January of 2015. At age 30, he’s one of the youngest members of the Illinois House. Originally from Chapel Hill, North Carolina, Guzzardi attended Brown University, where he graduated with a degree in comparative literature, and has lived in Logan Square ever since. He is passionate about education, and taught after school programs and tutored school children for many years.\nFriday March 8th\r\n5:30pm\nDePaul University\r\nCDM Theatre\r\n247 S. It’s time to set the record straight and credit the pioneering female filmmakers who changed cinema history. Filmmaker and DePaul professor Shayna Connelly invites you to learn about the female filmmakers who pushed the boundaries of cinematic form, starting with filmmakers such as Alice Guy-Blaché, Lois Weber and Germaine Dulac. Celebrate women’s history month with an introduction to the power and influence of these entrepreneurial women.\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\t    7:00 PM to 9:00 PM\r\n\t\t\t    \n\r\n\t\t\t\tChicago Filmmakers 5720 N. (CDM) at DePaul University invites you to attend our upcoming Graduate Financial Information Session.\n\r\nOur Financial Information Session provides admitted students a comprehensive presentation of the financial aid process, scholarships, and assistantship opportunities, and ways to help finance your advanced degree. There will also be an opportunity after the presentation to speak with a graduate admission officer and financial aid counselor.\n\r\nFor any questions about this event, please call (312) 362-8714.\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\t    12:00 PM to 1:00 PM\r\n\t\t\t    \n\r\n\t\t\t\tOnline\r\n\t\t\t\n\nRegister\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\tMar\r\n\t\t\t\n\r\n\t\t\t\t8\r\n\t\t\t\n\n\n\nCDM Graduate Admission Lunch & Learn: MS Cybersecurity and MS Network Engineering and Security\xa0\n\nEnjoy lunch on us with CDM faculty, current students, and graduate admissions to learn about our MS Cybersecurity and MS Network Engineering and Security programs through conversation in a casual, small setting.\n\r\nAt our Lunch & Learn, you will meet with cybersecurity and network engineering and security faculty members, discuss program interests, learn more about the application process and hear about our students? experiences.\n\r\nLunch and refreshments will be provided. For any questions about this event, please call (312) 362-8714.\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\t    12:30 PM to 1:30 PM\r\n\t\t\t    \n\r\n\t\t\t\tRichard M. and Maggie C. Daley Building - 14 E. Jackson Blvd., Ste. 507\r\n\t\t\t\n\nRegister\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\tMar\r\n\t\t\t\n\r\n\t\t\t\t8\r\n\t\t\t\n\n\n\nCDM Research Colloquium\xa0\n\nFor more information: http://colloquium.cdm.depaul.edu/ \n\n\r\n\t\t\t\t    1:00 PM to 2:00 PM\r\n\t\t\t    \n\r\n\t\t\t\tCDM 708\r\n\t\t\t\n\nNo registration is required for this event.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\tMar\r\n\t\t\t\n\r\n\t\t\t\t8\r\n\t\t\t\n\n\n\nVisiting Artists Series/Department of Mission and Ministry The 39th\xa0\n\nDePaul\'s Visiting Artists Series in partnership with the DePaul\'s Department of Mission and Ministry presents a screening and panel discussion about the feature documentary "The 39th"\nAmidst political scandal and fiscal crisis, 26-year-old activist Will Guzzardi believes that he can mobilize a movement to upend Illinois’ dysfunctional political system. But he chose to run against the daughter of one of the best connected politicians in Chicago — and the establishment is not going to let her go down without a fight. THE 39TH follows Guzzardi as he grows up, from activist to politician, and learns what it really takes for an outsider to win — and govern — within a political machine. TRAILER\xa0https://youtu.be/Ob6e5Cwmatg\nAn on-stage conversation immediately following the film with:\nLaura Fallsgraff\r\nDirector, The 39th\r\nAs Director of Engagement at Chicago production company Kindling Group, Laura Fallsgraff leads strategy and impact for feature films and digital campaigns. After writing for video and digital content for President Obama’s re-election campaign, she joined Kindling Group as a producer and impact producer, working on KG\'s films @home, Radical Grace, and No Small Matter. She premiered her first short documentary, The 39th, in 2017. She loves nothing more than bringing online organizing and compelling storytelling together to inspire change.\nFlonja Hoxha\xa0\r\nPrograms Assistant at Run for Something\r\nFlonja Hoxha is a a third-year studying Political Science at DePaul University. Born and raised in the Chicagoland area Flonja has interned and organized with various local, national, and issue campaigns. Most notably, Biss for Illinois and Hillary for America.\nWill Guzzardi\r\nState Representative, IL 39th District\r\nWill Guzzardi is a state representative from the 39th District, which includes parts of Logan Square, Avondale, Hermosa, Belmont Cragin and Portage Park. He’s been in the legislature since January of 2015. At age 30, he’s one of the youngest members of the Illinois House. Originally from Chapel Hill, North Carolina, Guzzardi attended Brown University, where he graduated with a degree in comparative literature, and has lived in Logan Square ever since. He is passionate about education, and taught after school programs and tutored school children for many years.\nFriday March 8th\r\n5:30pm\nDePaul University\r\nCDM Theatre\r\n247 S. State St. LL105\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\t    5:30 PM to 5:30 PM\r\n\t\t\t    \n\r\n\t\t\t\t247 S. LL107\r\n\t\t\t\n\nRegister\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\tMar\r\n\t\t\t\n\r\n\t\t\t\t15\r\n\t\t\t\n\n\n\nCDM Research Colloquium \xa0\n\n\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\t    1:00 PM to 2:00 PM\r\n\t\t\t    \n\r\n\t\t\t\tCDM 708\r\n\t\t\t\n\ncolloquium.cdm.depaul.edu \n\n\n\n\n\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\tMar\r\n\t\t\t\n\r\n\t\t\t\t15\r\n\t\t\t\n\n\n\nPhD 101\xa0\n\nLearn more about getting a PhD and pursuing research opportunities at CDM.\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\t    3:00 PM to 5:00 PM\r\n\t\t\t    \n\r\n\t\t\t\tCDM 708\r\n\t\t\t\n\nNo registration is required for this event.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\tMar\r\n\t\t\t\n\r\n\t\t\t\t16\r\n\t\t\t\n\n\n\nLecture- An Alternative History of Cinema: Female Pioneers\xa0\n\nLecture presented by Shayna Connelly\nWomen have played an integral role in cinema from the beginning, but their achievements have not always been recognized. It’s time to set the record straight and credit the pioneering female filmmakers who changed cinema history. Filmmaker and DePaul professor Shayna Connelly invites you to learn about the female filmmakers who pushed the boundaries of cinematic form, starting with filmmakers such as Alice Guy-Blaché, Lois Weber and Germaine Dulac. Celebrate women’s history month with an introduction to the power and influence of these entrepreneurial women.\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\t    7:00 PM to 9:00 PM\r\n\t\t\t    \n\r\n\t\t\t\tChicago Filmmakers 5720 N. Ridge Ave. 60660 Chicago , IL\r\n\t\t\t\n\nRegister\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\tMar\r\n\t\t\t\n\r\n\t\t\t\t21\r\n\t\t\t\n\n\n\nCDM New Graduate Student Orientation\xa0\n\nJoin your CDM Graduate Admission Officers for our New Graduate Orientation. Newly admitted students will learn how to register for classes, navigating Campus Connect, and useful tips for program management.    Meet one-on-one with your admission officer to discuss introductory course waivers, course recommendations and registering.    Check is at 3:45 p.m. and the presentation begins promptly at 4:00 p.m. Light refreshments will be provided.    This event is intended for newly admitted graduate students enrolling in the Spring Quarter 2019. For any questions about this event, please call (312) 362-8714.\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\t    4:00 PM to 7:00 PM\r\n\t\t\t    \n\r\n\t\t\t\tCDM Center - 243 S. 2019\xa0\n\nSCD Symposium 2019\nDePaul University’s College of Computing and Digital Media is proud to announce its 2019 Research Symposium (SCD – Research Symposium).\nThe event will feature student presentations and posters\xa0take place on:\nFriday May 31st, 2019\r\nCollege of Computing and Digital Media, room 924\r\n243 S Wabash Ave\r\nChicago, IL 60604\nThe event is a fantastic\xa0opportunity for students at all levels to present research or attend to engage with the research community at DePaul.\nThis year’s event is being sponsored by the Dean’s Office of the College of Computing and Digital Media (CDM) and organized by the PhD Student Council (PSC@CDM).\nSubmissions and requirements are clarified in the\xa0Call for Papers\xa0tab on the website.\nPlease RSVP if you plan to attend.\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\t    9:00 AM to 5:00 PM\r\n\t\t\t    \n\r\n\t\t\t\tCollege of Computing and Digital Media, room 924 243 S Wabash Ave Chicago, IL 60604\r\n\t\t\t\n\nRegister\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\r\n the financial aid process, scholarships, and assistantship opportunities, and ways to help finance your advanced degree. But he chose to run against the daughter of one of the best connected politicians in Chicago — and the establishment is not going to let her go down without a fight. THE 39TH follows Guzzardi as he grows up, from activist to politician, and learns what it really takes for an outsider to win — and govern — within a political machine. TRAILER\xa0https://youtu.be/Ob6e5Cwmatg\nAn on-stage conversation immediately following the film with:\nLaura Fallsgraff\r\nDirector, The 39th\r\nAs Director of Engagement at Chicago production company Kindling Group, Laura Fallsgraff leads strategy and impact for feature films and digital campaigns. After writing for video and digital content for President Obama’s re-election campaign, she joined Kindling Group as a producer and impact producer, working on KG\'s films @home, Radical Grace, and No Small Matter. She premiered her first short documentary, The 39th, in 2017. She loves nothing more than bringing online organizing and compelling storytelling together to inspire change.\nFlonja Hoxha\xa0\r\nPrograms Assistant at Run for Something\r\nFlonja Hoxha is a a third-year studying Political Science at DePaul University. Born and raised in the Chicagoland area Flonja has interned and organized with various local, national, and issue campaigns. Most notably, Biss for Illinois and Hillary for America.\nWill Guzzardi\r\nState Representative, IL 39th District\r\nWill Guzzardi is a state representative from the 39th District, which includes parts of Logan Square, Avondale, Hermosa, Belmont Cragin and Portage Park. He’s been in the legislature since January of 2015. At age 30, he’s one of the youngest members of the Illinois House. Originally from Chapel Hill, North Carolina, Guzzardi attended Brown University, where he graduated with a degree in comparative literature, and has lived in Logan Square ever since. He is passionate about education, and taught after school programs and tutored school children for many years.\nFriday March 8th\r\n5:30pm\nDePaul University\r\nCDM Theatre\r\n247 S. State St. LL105\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\t    5:30 PM to 5:30 PM\r\n\t\t\t    \n\r\n\t\t\t\t247 S. LL107\r\n\t\t\t\n\nRegister\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\tMar\r\n\t\t\t\n\r\n\t\t\t\t15\r\n\t\t\t\n\n\n\nCDM Research Colloquium \xa0\n\n\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\t    1:00 PM to 2:00 PM\r\n\t\t\t    \n\r\n\t\t\t\tCDM 708\r\n\t\t\t\n\ncolloquium.cdm.depaul.edu \n\n\n\n\n\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\tMar\r\n\t\t\t\n\r\n\t\t\t\t15\r\n\t\t\t\n\n\n\nPhD 101\xa0\n\nLearn more about getting a PhD and pursuing research opportunities at CDM.\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\t    3:00 PM to 5:00 PM\r\n\t\t\t    \n\r\n\t\t\t\tCDM 708\r\n\t\t\t\n\nNo registration is required for this event.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\tMar\r\n\t\t\t\n\r\n\t\t\t\t16\r\n\t\t\t\n\n\n\nLecture- An Alternative History of Cinema: Female Pioneers\xa0\n\nLecture presented by Shayna Connelly\nWomen have played an integral role in cinema from the beginning, but their achievements have not always been recognized. It’s time to set the record straight and credit the pioneering female filmmakers who changed cinema history. Filmmaker and DePaul professor Shayna Connelly invites you to learn about the female filmmakers who pushed the boundaries of cinematic form, starting with filmmakers such as Alice Guy-Blaché, Lois Weber and Germaine Dulac. Celebrate women’s history month with an introduction to the power and influence of these entrepreneurial women.\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\t    7:00 PM to 9:00 PM\r\n\t\t\t    \n\r\n\t\t\t\tChicago Filmmakers 5720 N. Newly admitted students will learn how to register for classes, navigating Campus Connect, and useful tips for program management.    Meet one-on-one with your admission officer to discuss introductory course waivers, course recommendations and registering.    Check is at 3:45 p.m. and the presentation begins promptly at 4:00 p.m. Light refreshments will be provided.    This event is intended for newly admitted graduate students enrolling in the Spring Quarter 2019. (CDM) at DePaul University invites you to attend our upcoming Graduate Financial Information Session.\n\r\nOur Financial Information Session provides admitted students a comprehensive presentation of the financial aid process, scholarships, and assistantship opportunities, and ways to help finance your advanced degree. There will also be an opportunity after the presentation to speak with a graduate admission officer and financial aid counselor.\n\r\nFor any questions about this event, please call (312) 362-8714.\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\t    12:00 PM to 1:00 PM\r\n\t\t\t    \n\r\n\t\t\t\tOnline\r\n\t\t\t\n\nRegister\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\tMar\r\n\t\t\t\n\r\n\t\t\t\t8\r\n\t\t\t\n\n\n\nCDM Graduate Admission Lunch & Learn: MS Cybersecurity and MS Network Engineering and Security\xa0\n\nEnjoy lunch on us with CDM faculty, current students, and graduate admissions to learn about our MS Cybersecurity and MS Network Engineering and Security programs through conversation in a casual, small setting.\n\r\nAt our Lunch & Learn, you will meet with cybersecurity and network engineering and security faculty members, discuss program interests, learn more about the application process and hear about our students? experiences.\n\r\nLunch and refreshments will be provided. For any questions about this event, please call (312) 362-8714.\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\t    12:30 PM to 1:30 PM\r\n\t\t\t    \n\r\n\t\t\t\tRichard M. and Maggie C. Daley Building - 14 E. Jackson Blvd., Ste. 507\r\n\t\t\t\n\nRegister\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\tMar\r\n\t\t\t\n\r\n\t\t\t\t8\r\n\t\t\t\n\n\n\nCDM Research Colloquium\xa0\n\nFor more information: http://colloquium.cdm.depaul.edu/ \n\n\r\n\t\t\t\t    1:00 PM to 2:00 PM\r\n\t\t\t    \n\r\n\t\t\t\tCDM 708\r\n\t\t\t\n\nNo registration is required for this event.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\tMar\r\n\t\t\t\n\r\n\t\t\t\t8\r\n\t\t\t\n\n\n\nVisiting Artists Series/Department of Mission and Ministry The 39th\xa0\n\nDePaul\'s Visiting Artists Series in partnership with the DePaul\'s Department of Mission and Ministry presents a screening and panel discussion about the feature documentary "The 39th"\nAmidst political scandal and fiscal crisis, 26-year-old activist Will Guzzardi believes that he can mobilize a movement to upend Illinois’ dysfunctional political system. But he chose to run against the daughter of one of the best connected politicians in Chicago — and the establishment is not going to let her go down without a fight. THE 39TH follows Guzzardi as he grows up, from activist to politician, and learns what it really takes for an outsider to win — and govern — within a political machine. TRAILER\xa0https://youtu.be/Ob6e5Cwmatg\nAn on-stage conversation immediately following the film with:\nLaura Fallsgraff\r\nDirector, The 39th\r\nAs Director of Engagement at Chicago production company Kindling Group, Laura Fallsgraff leads strategy and impact for feature films and digital campaigns. After writing for video and digital content for President Obama’s re-election campaign, she joined Kindling Group as a producer and impact producer, working on KG\'s films @home, Radical Grace, and No Small Matter. She premiered her first short documentary, The 39th, in 2017. She loves nothing more than bringing online organizing and compelling storytelling together to inspire change.\nFlonja Hoxha\xa0\r\nPrograms Assistant at Run for Something\r\nFlonja Hoxha is a a third-year studying Political Science at DePaul University. Born and raised in the Chicagoland area Flonja has interned and organized with various local, national, and issue campaigns. Most notably, Biss for Illinois and Hillary for America.\nWill Guzzardi\r\nState Representative, IL 39th District\r\nWill Guzzardi is a state representative from the 39th District, which includes parts of Logan Square, Avondale, Hermosa, Belmont Cragin and Portage Park. He’s been in the legislature since January of 2015. At age 30, he’s one of the youngest members of the Illinois House. Originally from Chapel Hill, North Carolina, Guzzardi attended Brown University, where he graduated with a degree in comparative literature, and has lived in Logan Square ever since. He is passionate about education, and taught after school programs and tutored school children for many years.\nFriday March 8th\r\n5:30pm\nDePaul University\r\nCDM Theatre\r\n247 S. State St. LL105\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\t    5:30 PM to 5:30 PM\r\n\t\t\t    \n\r\n\t\t\t\t247 S. It’s time to set the record straight and credit the pioneering female filmmakers who changed cinema history. Filmmaker and DePaul professor Shayna Connelly invites you to learn about the female filmmakers who pushed the boundaries of cinematic form, starting with filmmakers such as Alice Guy-Blaché, Lois Weber and Germaine Dulac. Celebrate women’s history month with an introduction to the power and influence of these entrepreneurial women.\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\t    7:00 PM to 9:00 PM\r\n\t\t\t    \n\r\n\t\t\t\tChicago Filmmakers 5720 N. (CDM) at DePaul University invites you to attend our upcoming Graduate Financial Information Session.\n\r\nOur Financial Information Session provides admitted students a comprehensive presentation of the financial aid process, scholarships, and assistantship opportunities, and ways to help finance your advanced degree. There will also be an opportunity after the presentation to speak with a graduate admission officer and financial aid counselor.\n\r\nFor any questions about this event, please call (312) 362-8714.\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\t    12:00 PM to 1:00 PM\r\n\t\t\t    \n\r\n\t\t\t\tOnline\r\n\t\t\t\n\nRegister\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\tMar\r\n\t\t\t\n\r\n\t\t\t\t8\r\n\t\t\t\n\n\n\nCDM Graduate Admission Lunch & Learn: MS Cybersecurity and MS Network Engineering and Security\xa0\n\nEnjoy lunch on us with CDM faculty, current students, and graduate admissions to learn about our MS Cybersecurity and MS Network Engineering and Security programs through conversation in a casual, small setting.\n\r\nAt our Lunch & Learn, you will meet with cybersecurity and network engineering and security faculty members, discuss program interests, learn more about the application process and hear about our students? experiences.\n\r\nLunch and refreshments will be provided. For any questions about this event, please call (312) 362-8714.\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\t    12:30 PM to 1:30 PM\r\n\t\t\t    \n\r\n\t\t\t\tRichard M. and Maggie C. Daley Building - 14 E. Jackson Blvd., Ste. 507\r\n\t\t\t\n\nRegister\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\tMar\r\n\t\t\t\n\r\n\t\t\t\t8\r\n\t\t\t\n\n\n\nCDM Research Colloquium\xa0\n\nFor more information: http://colloquium.cdm.depaul.edu/ \n\n\r\n\t\t\t\t    1:00 PM to 2:00 PM\r\n\t\t\t    \n\r\n\t\t\t\tCDM 708\r\n\t\t\t\n\nNo registration is required for this event.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\tMar\r\n\t\t\t\n\r\n\t\t\t\t8\r\n\t\t\t\n\n\n\nVisiting Artists Series/Department of Mission and Ministry The 39th\xa0\n\nDePaul\'s Visiting Artists Series in partnership with the DePaul\'s Department of Mission and Ministry presents a screening and panel discussion about the feature documentary "The 39th"\nAmidst political scandal and fiscal crisis, 26-year-old activist Will Guzzardi believes that he can mobilize a movement to upend Illinois’ dysfunctional political system. But he chose to run against the daughter of one of the best connected politicians in Chicago — and the establishment is not going to let her go down without a fight. THE 39TH follows Guzzardi as he grows up, from activist to politician, and learns what it really takes for an outsider to win — and govern — within a political machine. TRAILER\xa0https://youtu.be/Ob6e5Cwmatg\nAn on-stage conversation immediately following the film with:\nLaura Fallsgraff\r\nDirector, The 39th\r\nAs Director of Engagement at Chicago production company Kindling Group, Laura Fallsgraff leads strategy and impact for feature films and digital campaigns. After writing for video and digital content for President Obama’s re-election campaign, she joined Kindling Group as a producer and impact producer, working on KG\'s films @home, Radical Grace, and No Small Matter. She premiered her first short documentary, The 39th, in 2017. She loves nothing more than bringing online organizing and compelling storytelling together to inspire change.\nFlonja Hoxha\xa0\r\nPrograms Assistant at Run for Something\r\nFlonja Hoxha is a a third-year studying Political Science at DePaul University. Born and raised in the Chicagoland area Flonja has interned and organized with various local, national, and issue campaigns. Most notably, Biss for Illinois and Hillary for America.\nWill Guzzardi\r\nState Representative, IL 39th District\r\nWill Guzzardi is a state representative from the 39th District, which includes parts of Logan Square, Avondale, Hermosa, Belmont Cragin and Portage Park. He’s been in the legislature since January of 2015. At age 30, he’s one of the youngest members of the Illinois House. Originally from Chapel Hill, North Carolina, Guzzardi attended Brown University, where he graduated with a degree in comparative literature, and has lived in Logan Square ever since. He is passionate about education, and taught after school programs and tutored school children for many years.\nFriday March 8th\r\n5:30pm\nDePaul University\r\nCDM Theatre\r\n247 S. It’s time to set the record straight and credit the pioneering female filmmakers who changed cinema history. Filmmaker and DePaul professor Shayna Connelly invites you to learn about the female filmmakers who pushed the boundaries of cinematic form, starting with filmmakers such as Alice Guy-Blaché, Lois Weber and Germaine Dulac. Celebrate women’s history month with an introduction to the power and influence of these entrepreneurial women.\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\t    7:00 PM to 9:00 PM\r\n\t\t\t    \n\r\n\t\t\t\tChicago Filmmakers 5720 N. (CDM) at DePaul University invites you to attend our upcoming Graduate Financial Information Session.\n\r\nOur Financial Information Session provides admitted students a comprehensive presentation of the financial aid process, scholarships, and assistantship opportunities, and ways to help finance your advanced degree. There will also be an opportunity after the presentation to speak with a graduate admission officer and financial aid counselor.\n\r\nFor any questions about this event, please call (312) 362-8714.\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\t    12:00 PM to 1:00 PM\r\n\t\t\t    \n\r\n\t\t\t\tOnline\r\n\t\t\t\n\nRegister\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\tMar\r\n\t\t\t\n\r\n\t\t\t\t8\r\n\t\t\t\n\n\n\nCDM Graduate Admission Lunch & Learn: MS Cybersecurity and MS Network Engineering and Security\xa0\n\nEnjoy lunch on us with CDM faculty, current students, and graduate admissions to learn about our MS Cybersecurity and MS Network Engineering and Security programs through conversation in a casual, small setting.\n\r\nAt our Lunch & Learn, you will meet with cybersecurity and network engineering and security faculty members, discuss program interests, learn more about the application process and hear about our students? experiences.\n\r\nLunch and refreshments will be provided. For any questions about this event, please call (312) 362-8714.\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\t    12:30 PM to 1:30 PM\r\n\t\t\t    \n\r\n\t\t\t\tRichard M. and Maggie C. Daley Building - 14 E. Jackson Blvd., Ste. 507\r\n\t\t\t\n\nRegister\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\tMar\r\n\t\t\t\n\r\n\t\t\t\t8\r\n\t\t\t\n\n\n\nCDM Research Colloquium\xa0\n\nFor more information: http://colloquium.cdm.depaul.edu/ \n\n\r\n\t\t\t\t    1:00 PM to 2:00 PM\r\n\t\t\t    \n\r\n\t\t\t\tCDM 708\r\n\t\t\t\n\nNo registration is required for this event.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\tMar\r\n\t\t\t\n\r\n\t\t\t\t8\r\n\t\t\t\n\n\n\nVisiting Artists Series/Department of Mission and Ministry The 39th\xa0\n\nDePaul\'s Visiting Artists Series in partnership with the DePaul\'s Department of Mission and Ministry presents a screening and panel discussion about the feature documentary "The 39th"\nAmidst political scandal and fiscal crisis, 26-year-old activist Will Guzzardi believes that he can mobilize a movement to upend Illinois’ dysfunctional political system. But he chose to run against the daughter of one of the best connected politicians in Chicago — and the establishment is not going to let her go down without a fight. THE 39TH follows Guzzardi as he grows up, from activist to politician, and learns what it really takes for an outsider to win — and govern — within a political machine. TRAILER\xa0https://youtu.be/Ob6e5Cwmatg\nAn on-stage conversation immediately following the film with:\nLaura Fallsgraff\r\nDirector, The 39th\r\nAs Director of Engagement at Chicago production company Kindling Group, Laura Fallsgraff leads strategy and impact for feature films and digital campaigns. After writing for video and digital content for President Obama’s re-election campaign, she joined Kindling Group as a producer and impact producer, working on KG\'s films @home, Radical Grace, and No Small Matter. She premiered her first short documentary, The 39th, in 2017. She loves nothing more than bringing online organizing and compelling storytelling together to inspire change.\nFlonja Hoxha\xa0\r\nPrograms Assistant at Run for Something\r\nFlonja Hoxha is a a third-year studying Political Science at DePaul University. Born and raised in the Chicagoland area Flonja has interned and organized with various local, national, and issue campaigns. Most notably, Biss for Illinois and Hillary for America.\nWill Guzzardi\r\nState Representative, IL 39th District\r\nWill Guzzardi is a state representative from the 39th District, which includes parts of Logan Square, Avondale, Hermosa, Belmont Cragin and Portage Park. He’s been in the legislature since January of 2015. At age 30, he’s one of the youngest members of the Illinois House. Originally from Chapel Hill, North Carolina, Guzzardi attended Brown University, where he graduated with a degree in comparative literature, and has lived in Logan Square ever since. He is passionate about education, and taught after school programs and tutored school children for many years.\nFriday March 8th\r\n5:30pm\nDePaul University\r\nCDM Theatre\r\n247 S. State St. LL105\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\t    5:30 PM to 5:30 PM\r\n\t\t\t    \n\r\n\t\t\t\t247 S. It’s time to set the record straight and credit the pioneering female filmmakers who changed cinema history. Filmmaker and DePaul professor Shayna Connelly invites you to learn about the female filmmakers who pushed the boundaries of cinematic form, starting with filmmakers such as Alice Guy-Blaché, Lois Weber and Germaine Dulac. Celebrate women’s history month with an introduction to the power and influence of these entrepreneurial women.\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\t    7:00 PM to 9:00 PM\r\n\t\t\t    \n\r\n\t\t\t\tChicago Filmmakers 5720 N. Ridge Ave. 60660 Chicago , IL\r\n\t\t\t\n\nRegister\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\r\n\t\t\t\tMar\r\n\t\t\t\n\r\n\t\t\t\t21\r\n\t\t\t\n\n\n\nCDM New Graduate Student Orientation\xa0\n\nJoin your CDM Graduate Admission Officers for our New Graduate Orientation. Newly admitted students will learn how to register for classes, navigating Campus Connect, and useful tips for program management.    Meet one-on-one with your admission officer to discuss introductory course waivers, course recommendations and registering.    Check is at 3:45 p.m. and the presentation begins promptly at 4:00 p.m. Light refreshments will be provided.    This event is intended for newly admitted graduate students enrolling in the Spring Quarter 2019.
